@Miguel: I like this idea, that user get such error. However  current changes can only affect documentation (according previous patch) and as we wanted some list/show commands (I hope to see it in the separate patch later).

So if you want to raise some error based on current support status, some mechanism, which allows it, should be implemented before. 

Correct me, if I understood your idea wrong.'}, {'account_id': 12606, 'date': '2015-06-02 21:46:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1

But for this patch what I'd like to see is that these helpful suggestions we have as status messages on deprecated entities are also kept once the entities become hidden. This will enable these more meaningful error messages to be delivered to the user with some simple changes to the patch that does the validation of the hidden resources/properties/attributes.

I'm going to remove my -1, since we can really improve on this later, happy to propose something myself after the support for hidden is merged."}, {'account_id': 4571, 'date': '2015-06-02 22:45:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

This class manages the /etc/iproute2/rt_tables file to assign each
scope id a unique routing table.  It uses a namespace specific table

commit_message:
Add a route table manager

This class manages the /etc/iproute2/rt_tables file to assign each
scope id a unique routing table.  It uses a namespace specific table
so that the table in the root namespace remains untouched.

Change-Id: Ibdbaff4717d04948a11afadb421e625de072888a
Partially-implements:  blueprint address-scopes

commit_message:
DB downgrades are no longer supported

Commit 7aa4b75da9722496c4e166b44cc04973fd441f52 added a DB downgrade
test. This is no longer supported (since commit
e2e846f74b057f5f3ed72312b0b0ccf6ef97add2)

TrivialFix

commit_message:
Support recommendations in CDH plugin

We should support autoconfigurable hadoop configs in CDH plugin.
This patch does this job.

Implements bluprint: recommend-configuration

Change-Id: I3d938236786aae8f5e923a3fc3ef35ba24630e74

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-02-05 16:32:45.000000000', 'message': 'Introduced "naming conventions" SA feature

In the current state some constraints has no defined names in the
project.

So they are generated by DB engine automatically and each DB generates
constraint names in its own fashion. This makes difficult to operate
with constraints, for example in migrations, where they should be
referred by names.

SQLAlchemy provides the feature for generation of constraint names
using patterns [1].

Leveraging it will bring consistency to constraints naming
in the project.

***IMPORTANT***

This revision also drops old migrations and starts migration from
scratch. It causes backward-incompatibility with previous versions.

Also SQLite support is dropped, migrations are no longer compatible with
this engine. It is no logner recommended to use it even for development.
However those who still wants to use SQLite can use introduced commands
"register_models" and "unregister_models". The first one generates
"CREATE TABLE" statements and syncs DB with models in one pass. The
second one does opposite.

[1] http://alembic.readthedocs.org/en/latest/naming.html#tutorial-constraint-names

Change-Id: Ie55843347c8bf0cbec162b1cfd2bad4d5fac1234
Related-Bug: #1399151

commit_message:
Introduced "naming conventions" SA feature

In the current state some constraints has no defined names in the
project.

So they are generated by DB engine automatically and each DB generates
constraint names in its own fashion. This makes difficult to operate
with constraints, for example in migrations, where they should be
referred by names.

SQLAlchemy provides the feature for generation of constraint names
using patterns [1].

Leveraging it will bring consistency to constraints naming
in the project.

***IMPORTANT***

This revision also drops old migrations and starts migration from
scratch. It causes backward-incompatibility with previous versions.

Also SQLite support is dropped, migrations are no longer compatible with
this engine. It is no longer recommended to use it even for development.
However those who still wants to use SQLite can use introduced commands
"register_models" and "unregister_models". The first one generates
"CREATE TABLE" statements and syncs DB with models in one pass. The
second one does opposite.

[1] http://alembic.readthedocs.org/en/latest/naming.html#tutorial-constraint-names

Change-Id: Ie55843347c8bf0cbec162b1cfd2bad4d5fac1234
Related-Bug: #1399151

commit_message:
Fix Create User form's fields sorting for Django 1.7

Starting from Django 1.7 self.fields.keyOrder no longer works for
setting fields ordering, need to rearrange fields there by recreating
underlying OrderedDict.

Change-Id: If0f4c7014a7a68f2ff0d0f2cb06f7b1c2e28436b
Closes-Bug: #1465221

commit_message:
Drop OVS & LB monolitic plugins

OVS & LB monolitic plugins have been dropped from Neutron in Juno and
have been replaced in Havana by ML2 (in neutron::plugins::ml2::X and
neutron::agents::ml2::X).
It's time to clean this module by dropping useless plugins.

Change-Id: I62ecd46fbc74f3e30b66052a7f95ee7c96c3138f

We currently default swift_allow_all_users in
etc/openstack_deploy/user_variables.yml instead of
playbooks/roles/os_swift/defaults/main.yml.  If a deployer removes this
variable from etc/openstack_deploy/user_variables.yml, the swift
playbook will fail.  This commit moves the variable default to
playbooks/roles/os_swift/defaults/main.yml.

commit_message:
Move swift_allow_all_users to role defaults

We currently default swift_allow_all_users in
etc/openstack_deploy/user_variables.yml instead of
playbooks/roles/os_swift/defaults/main.yml.  If a deployer removes this
variable from etc/openstack_deploy/user_variables.yml, the swift
playbook will fail.  This commit moves the variable default to
playbooks/roles/os_swift/defaults/main.yml.

Change-Id: I9a73eda990327bf427f40a13965484fde00cbe21
Closes-Bug: #1424981
(cherry picked from commit 495f8b31d6400b50d0c64bba7ede7cbc4b181d23)

commit_message:
Enable python34 tests for nova/tests/unit/virt/vmwareapi/test*.py

Two tests still need work, they are commented out in tox.ini
py34 target as a reminder. All other tests in
nova/tests/unit/virt/vmwareapi/test*.py were added to the py34
tox target

Change-Id: I4739822765af2af65f012e53c278933720cf2650

commit_message:
Block deploy/provision action for unassigned nodes

If user will try to provision or deploy node that is not
assigned to any environment, error will be printed.
Also removed required "env" param for deploy/provision
action since it's not used there.

Change-Id: I3787c50cb5284b43cbb44261da000baf040cc684
Closes-Bug: #1445531

commit_message:
Amend resource objects proposal

We agreed that Usage wasn't the most useful term. Rewrite in terms of
Inventories.

Get rid of the conductor RPC method - we'll just use ComputeNode#save.

Fix some minor nits.

Change-Id: Idceba6dd53e4c4827e37f9e01b34a89455783d39

[{'created': '2015-06-12 13:20:07.000000000', 'message': "Replace dict(obj.iteritems() with dict(obj)

Since oslo.db 1.10, it's possible to convert directly a SQLAlchemy
object to a dictionary using dict(obj) instead of having to write
dict(obj.iteritems()).

commit_message:
Replace dict(obj.iteritems() with dict(obj)

Since oslo.db 1.10, it's possible to convert directly a SQLAlchemy
object to a dictionary using dict(obj) instead of having to write
dict(obj.iteritems()).

dict(obj) works also on regular dictionaries to duplicate a dictionary.

Blueprint cinder-python3
Change-Id: I868a055d5bbfe6646aad3e36e1bf6c7a1ad7b449

[{'created': '2015-04-23 17:50:02.000000000', 'message': 'Add cinder::scheduler::filter for managing scheduler.filter

This patch is aim to add a new class to manage the filter

commit_message:
Set MURANO_REPOSITORY_URL for client tests

Since murano-ci job is checked for every commit to python-muranoclient
and this include testing repository functionality, MURANO_REPOSITORY_URL
has to be set for such tests. This change should unblock client gate.

Change-Id: I923fdb4792fa3253e108e781bba2776b88aa902f
Closes-Bug: #1465632

commit_message:
Path to mysql-wss script in DB backup/restore doc

In the Fuel 6.1 Operations Guide, path to mysql-wss is incorrect in
db-backup-ops.rst file.

It is now /usr/lib/ocf/resource.d/fuel/mysql-wss, not
/usr/lib/ocf/resource.d/mirantis/mysql-wss.

Change-Id: I0aa561a9803493da45e0b023b5623f540e03de08
Closes-bug: 1464755

commit_message:
Connect RPM repo to master during patching env

In order to deliver patches for puppet manifests
on OpenStack environments, tests should be able to
update 'fuel-library' package on master node (during
tests for environment patching). Add additional
setting for specifying custom repositories which must be
connected to master node.

Change-Id: I4f68e31ebba67b87652aed15fc894b006e603c81
Implements: blueprint mos-patching-tests

on OpenStack environments, tests should be able to

We are rebuilding our pypi mirror which will take about 8 hours, switch
to pypi while this is ongoing in order to unblock CI.

Addresses UcsSdk install issue

used.

Change-Id: I83ee57c6a516b5382d074c0082525ad7feadd59c
'}, {'created': '2015-02-24 10:28:37.000000000', 'message': 'Implement private share_types

Implements bp private-share-types

Change-Id: I83ee57c6a516b5382d074c0082525ad7feadd59c
'}, {'created': '2015-02-25 14:13:41.000000000', 'message': 'Implement private share_types

Add share_type_access extension which introduces 
the ability to manage share type access:
* Share types are public by default
* Private share types can be created by setting
  the is_public boolean field to False at creation time.
* Access to a private share type can be controlled
  by adding or removing a project from it.
* Private share types without projects are only visible
  by users with the admin role/context.
Implementation details and unit tests were mostly adapted
from Cinder and Nova access extensions.

commit_message:
Implement private share_types

Add share_type_access extension which introduces
the ability to manage share type access:
* Share types are public by default
* Private share types can be created by setting
  the is_public boolean field to False at creation time.
* Access to a private share type can be controlled
  by adding or removing a project from it.
* Private share types without projects are only visible
  by users with the admin role/context.
Implementation details and unit tests were mostly adapted
from Cinder and Nova access extensions.

Implements bp private-share-types

Change-Id: I83ee57c6a516b5382d074c0082525ad7feadd59c

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-06-10 07:07:56.000000000', 'message': "Configurable lxc cache and rootfs path

The rootfs of the containers uses large disk spaces and is defaulted to
/var/lib/lxc. It's desirable to configure an alternative rootfs directory on a
partition with large enough disk space to hold the rootfs.

The rootfs of a container is hard-linked to the lxc cache when created by lxc
templates. Therefore they have to reside on the same partition and the lxc
cache shall be configurable as well as the rootfs directory.

The lxc-ubuntu template is patched by lxc-host role to use the configured lxc
cache folder.

To confgiure these parameters, set the following variables in global_overrides
of openstack_user_config.yml:
    - lxc_container_directory, defaults to /var/lib/lxc
    - lxc_container_cache_path, defaults to /var/cache/lxc

Change-Id: I9ccf0c45e0a1875644750e0d70ce613265040176
"}, {'created': '2015-06-10 16:49:56.000000000', 'message': "Configurable lxc cache and rootfs path

commit_message:
Configurable lxc cache and rootfs path

The rootfs of the containers use large disk space and is defaulted to
/var/lib/lxc. It's desirable to configure an alternative rootfs directory on a
partition with large enough free space to hold the rootfs.

The rootfs of a container is hard-linked to the lxc cache when created by lxc
templates. Therefore both have to reside on the same partition and the lxc
cache shall be configurable as well as the rootfs directory.

The lxc-ubuntu template is patched by lxc-host role to use the configured lxc
cache folder. This patch should be removed once the updated upstream lxc with
support of configuring the cache path goes mainstream.

To confgiure these parameters, set the following variables in global_overrides
of openstack_user_config.yml:
    - lxc_container_directory, defaults to /var/lib/lxc
    - lxc_container_cache_path, defaults to /var/cache/lxc

Closes-Bug: #1463905
Change-Id: I9ccf0c45e0a1875644750e0d70ce613265040176

commit_message:
Set default pass in aio scripts to be random

In the bootstrap-aio.sh and osad-aio-heat-template.yml we use a default
password of "secrete". As a minor security concern, this patch adjusts
this to be random.

Change-Id: I54b9a085aba7845b7a9ad435c60604359921fc09
Closes-Bug: #1462000

commit_message:
Switch put_update to patch_update

As PUT updates are the great majority, and PATCH is only used in a
handful of places, swap out this name and the behavior so that PUT is
the default. Identity v3 and one resource in Image v2 use PATCH for
their updates, so they enable it.

Change-Id: I3f7ed19f050a0c6477f1b91112ff2dc4e1fc2528
Closes-Bug: 1427479

Christian, yes, you are right. But I think this whole "render index.rst as slides" is wrong. Do you know how to persuade sphinx/hieroglyph to generate "normal" pages with links to the slide "chapters"? Perhaps we can delete this index and substitute it with custom index.html in the tox.ini?'}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2015-05-28 07:15:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I will have a look.'}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2015-05-28 07:28:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

This is intentional. According to https://hieroglyph.readthedocs.org/en/hieroglyph-0.5.5/getting-started.html#authoring-slides the index.rst file will be interpreted as a slide. Maybe it is better to generate one set of slides for each RST file instead of generating all slides based on the index.rst file? I will propose an other patchset for this. Independent of this we can remove the indices and tables from the index.rst.'}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2015-05-28 10:42:17.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2015-05-28 10:43:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

What do you think about this? This way we have a generated index.html file including all slides and we have a generated html file for each available rst file only containing the slides defined there.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-28 10:47:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-training-guides-tox-doc-publish-checkbuild http://docs-draft.openstack.org/46/185946/2/check/gate-training-guides-tox-doc-publish-checkbuild/6cd21f3//publish-docs/ : SUCCESS in 1m 34s
- gate-training-guides-tox-slides http://logs.openstack.org/46/185946/2/check/gate-training-guides-tox-slides/f88cf27/ : SUCCESS in 1m 33s'}, {'account_id': 7007, 'date': '2015-05-28 13:23:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2

Matjaz, I suggest that we move other slides in the same format!'}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2015-05-28 13:47:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

We could add a index2.html file containing an table of contents with all separated generated slide files.'}, {'account_id': 11889, 'date': '2015-05-28 14:08:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

sure, this is much better than old autogenerated index. I am concerned a bit about navigability of unified slide deck - it's almost 200 slides, and this theme's slides index (table of contents that you get when you press "t" when looking at slides) is not so useful... Landscape's table of content is better.

We could tackle this with second index file, as you suggested, or maybe even resolve this outside index.rst by putting detailed links and unified view of the material on the landing page for Training guides project?'}, {'account_id': 287, 'date': '2015-05-28 17:56:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I'm not a fan of having one massive file for all the slides. I think the solution would be to build one index.html that is a standard html sphynx page, without the slides theme applied.

I think the solution lies around the options of hiero, like a different theme for the index page or a noslide 

https://hieroglyph.readthedocs.org/en/hieroglyph-0.5.5/config.html#hieroglyph-configuration

https://hieroglyph.readthedocs.org/en/hieroglyph-0.5.5/advanced.html#document-configuration

BTW, are we limiting ourselves to version 0.5.5?"}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2015-05-28 18:03:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Workflow-1

Makes sense to me. I will change this tomorrow. Not sure about the version of hieroglyph. I try to build the upstream training guide with the latest version tomorrow.'}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2015-06-16 11:47:58.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

commit_message:
[upstream-training] improve the index.rst file

* remove the "Indices and tables" slide

There is no need for a "Indices and tables" slide. The slide is
confusing and should be removed.

* convert the index.rst file from a default Sphinx documentation
  index.rst file into a more useful hieroglyph index.rst file

Change-Id: I52f134f2bc0437d974c7a06172bf5f9d043f55bb

commit_message:
Revert "Revert "change the default to PyMYSQL""

Some projects (Neutron) seem to be affected more than others, so we should revert this
to allow for a more selective choice of the DB driver on a per project basis.

We can re-enable the use MySQL-python just for Neutron.

This reverts commit de8d29ed8ce4a26b61cbee48f9fe5418d5416a06.

Related-Bug: #1464612

Change-Id: I889f4f8b116c413b300ab9eecc7b428a9a4afb1a

commit_message:
Add required devel packages for python-qpid-proton

python-qpid-proton does something similar to pyzmq when libzmq is not
installed. It bundles the underlying library and builds it.
Unfortunately, python-qpid-proton currently has a dependency on
`uuid-dev` and `swig` to build the python module.

These dependencies are being relaxed but it won't be until the next
release that we'll be able to live without them. Until then, I'm adding
these packages to the list of required packages.

Change-Id: Icb22b710d2a7eeaed6d8fa55a389077204d1f8d9

commit_message:
Providers should use auth_uri if available

The old auth_host/auth_port/auth_protocol parameters are deprecated in
the manifests, but the provider code hasn't been updated to allow
getting rid of them.  This changes the providers to use auth_uri if
available and fallback to using the old parameters if auth_uri isn't
available.

Change-Id: I5ae48f9cdeca656d1d8344a004cdc30202dffb6d

Release Notes 6.1 -- New Features (Fuel)

This commit provides RN for the following
features:

- granular task-based deployment
- rendering graph
- network verification before deployment
- remove node from inventory
- role operations

Change-Id: I5bca9c6c2982c2d9c571e438658e9bfece03dabd
Implements: blueprint granular-deployment-based-on-tasks
Related-Bug: 1415520
Implements: blueprint remove-node-from-fuel-inventory

commit_message:
Allow protocol to be set per endpoint-type

If services are running behind an SSL terminating LB you will want to
differentiate between protocol on internalURL and publicURL endpoints.
This patch allows you to set the values of protocol per endpoint type,
but doesn't change the default behaviour which is to have it set in one
var.

Change-Id: I7a74c85a8841499623746586ae27103a71c6fec0
Partial-Bug: #1399383

commit_message:
Replace dict.iteritems() with dict.items()

This change adds Python 3 compatibility to the modified code.

Replace also six.iteritems(obj) with obj.items().

The iteritems() method of Python 2 dictionaries was renamed to items()
on Python 3. As discussed on the openstack-dev mailing list, iteritems()
must be replaced with items(), six.iteritems() should not be used. In
OpenStack, the overhead of creating a temporary list with dict.items()
on Python 2 is negligible.

Blueprint cinder-python3
Change-Id: Ic3d8fd6b71d2c9f21929b0d6bf68c8f84a5e2567

commit_message:
Allow to run patching on pre-defined tests

- Add variable to settings.py to specify particular test
to run patching on
- Modify map_tests() function to set as patching dependent test
that was exported

Change-Id: I2fd5e74343f334d59f341aa3f0700134cd902de4
Implements: blueprint mos-patching-tests

commit_message:
Release Notes 6.1 - New Features (Partner)

This commit contains the following new partner features:

* dual hypervisor support
* multiple cinder types support
* VMware Settings tab on the Fuel web UI
* Mellanox Infiniband

Change-Id: I27250ccfe3fb5ae719151e3b104dc74e5128301e
Implements: blueprint vmware-dual-hypervisor
Implements: blueprint cinder-vmdk-role
Implements: blueprint vmware-ui-settings

commit_message:
Support multiple filenames for package commands

Before only a single package/bundle could be imported and deleted at a time.
This commit introduces support for multiple positional arguments in
bundle-import and package-import and package-delete commands.

Package and bundle dependencies are tracked in a single
dictionary during import. This means, that importing 2 packages,
that have common dependency-package would cause that package
to be imported only once.

Since it is highly complicated to specify --version for multiple
positional arguments with argparse this option is ignored, when used
with multiple packages.

Closes-Bug: #1441204
Partially-implements: blueprint multiple-positional-arguments
Change-Id: Id06c642d88f7d2a2726aec56e753c8db7dcc8ceb

commit_message:
[Manila] Add context for Manila quotas

Add context for following Manila quotas:
- shares
- gigabytes
- snapshots
- snapshot_gigabytes
- share_networks

And set default values as unlimited (-1).

Change-Id: Ie92f9ba03b5229984ee8b148d4bef715693c31e7

commit_message:
Remove db layer hard-code permission checks for quota_get_all_*

This patch removes the hard-code permission checks for db call
quota_get_all_*

For v2 API, there is same project owner hard-code permission checks
at REST API layer, so nothing we need to for it.

For v2.1, adds the 'target' for policy enforcement that used to
enforce owner checks. The default method use same rule with show
method before. After removed hard-code permission checks for show
method, this patch adds new rule for distinguish different permission
of defaults and show.

Partially implements bp nova-api-policy-final-part

UpgradeImpact: Due to the db layer permission checks was deleted. The
default rule is added to "os_compute_api:os-quota-sets:show" for
matching the same permission as before. Show and default action are
shared same rule before. But after the cleanup, those two methods have
different permission. So add new rule for default action
"os_compute_api:os-quota-sets:defaults".

Change-Id: I63f180770a9199046452be7ad6e031a142d3c79d

commit_message:
Introduce gnocchi-metricd

This daemon is responsible for treating new measures that are sent to
storage drivers and must be run in background.

Also add a thread in the gabbi ConfigFixture to do metricd
processing. Without this the new async processing of measures will
cause tests that check to see if measures were created will fail.
Meanwhile gabbi >=0.100.0 provides a 'poll' function so that tests
will try a few times for what they are looking for.

The tests in resource.yaml have been cleaned up to insure that they
are testing a specific resource and its measures, not an ambiguous
last-in-the-list member of resources. async.yaml confirms the async
handling.

The 'file' storage driver has been adjusted to make sure that writes
of aggregation files are atomic (by writing to a tmp file that is
renamed. Without this it is possible for files to exist but be read
as being empty.

Co-Authored-By: Chris Dent <chdent@redhat.com>
Change-Id: I0fd449ee82073edafca7673d00c69e61f75bb7d0

(2 comments)

LGTM, thanks.
A couple of comments inline.'}, {'account_id': 5196, 'date': '2015-03-07 04:41:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

(7 comments)

So I really wanted to +A this, because I feel while this isn't perfect most of the issues are something we can sort out in code review. Instead of bikeshedding on options missing from the help or things we don't fully agree on. But, I think we probably will need another rev here.

I'm a soft -1 (meaning I probably could be convinced to change my vote) here mostly because of the use of cli_tools. I took a look at it on pypi page and Kevin Mitchell's github repo for the project and it looks like it's not the most active project, he hasn't really touched it in a year. It's also not listed in global requirements (which isn't a deal breaker necessarily) which made me think are there tools in use by other openstack projects to do this type of interface. I saw cliff, which IIRC is what the openstack client is using to make the cli. Would cliff be something that would be a good fit for this effort? 

I just want to make sure cli_tools is the right basket to put our eggs in before we go and implement the new cli. Especially because I feel like the cli tooling space should have a bunch of options already, I'm not sure what looks like Vek's pet project is the right direction. That being said I do like the interface and would probably be ok with going that route if there is a reason to. I just think we need to raise the concern.

This coupled with my inline comments makes me think there needs to be another rev on this before we can say this is the direction we want to take for writing the CLI interface."}, {'account_id': 1192, 'date': '2015-03-10 16:02:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

In addition to inline comments, I think it is important that these commands be callable through a python api. This should not be hard to do and would make it easier for tempest to be consumed by other tools such as rally.'}, {'account_id': 6172, 'date': '2015-03-10 16:11:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1

David, 

I am not sure that Rally will be able to consume tempest as lib directly. 
Major issue is that Rally supports py26/27/34 and tempest doesn't (for now). 

But in any case I am looking for CLI api that will simplify life, especially if we will have command like

   tempest config generate --os-username admin --os-password admin ....

and 

  tempest start --regexp[--set] --output subunit.log


That will simplify life a lot."}, {'account_id': 10644, 'date': '2015-03-11 15:03:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

(6 comments)

mtreinish: I am not married to cli_tools and wasn't really aware of how openstack global requirements worked at the time of writing the spec.  I went down this road after working with Rally, they are using a home grown decorator that implements the same pattern, which I liked.  I believe the same exact functionality can be implemented without cli_tools using arg_parse alone.

dkranz: All calls should be available through python API as part of implementation.

boris: looks like config will not be part of initial cli effort with the addition of --output arg we should be able to meet your tempest run scenario:
tempest run --regexp[--set] --output subunit.stream.  

That would work right?"}, {'account_id': 10644, 'date': '2015-03-11 15:04:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Thanks to all for your input.'}, {'account_id': 5689, 'date': '2015-03-27 17:17:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

This bp looks good basically. I'll +2 after updated for some others comments.

BTW, when tempest-cli will be implemented, are we able to remove run_tempest.sh?"}, {'account_id': 5689, 'date': '2015-04-06 02:03:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

Add blueprint for tempest cli improvements

Added WIP branch to use for cli design discussion.
Please see:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/148611/
Checkout that commit and install tempest using
setup tools. From there use help system for proposed
CLI UX.

commit_message:
Replace it.next() with next(it) for py3 compat

The Python 2 next() method of iterators was renamed to __next__() on
Python 3. Use the builtin next() function instead which works on Python
2 and Python 3.

Change-Id: Ic948bc574b58f1d28c5c58e3985906dee17fa51d

commit_message:
Improve _find_network_host function in nmanager

VMware integration assumes using fake host parameter. For this reason
when we launch test "Check network connectivity from instance" ostf
has to use special function _find_network_host which return real
hostname where nova-network runs.

This function uses command 'pcs status' for requests pacemaker/corosync
system. When some nodes of corosync cluster fails this command works
really slow and test can't meet the timeout.

This patch-set changes slow 'pcs status' to 'crm_mon -1' which realizes
same behavior but faster.

Change-Id: I80e645ec9da5f4421182bef10f368a3e5c73258d
Closes-bug: #1465268
(cherry picked from commit 573eac27e4f5a7765a65ae3afa862f52bf867a4e)

commit_message:
Improve _find_network_host function in nmanager

VMware integration assumes using fake host parameter. For this reason
when we launch test "Check network connectivity from instance" ostf
has to use special function _find_network_host which return real
hostname where nova-network runs.

This function uses command 'pcs status' for requests pacemaker/corosync
system. When some nodes of corosync cluster fails this command works
really slow and test can't meet the timeout.

This patch-set changes slow 'pcs status' to 'crm_mon -1' which realizes
same behavior but faster.

Change-Id: I80e645ec9da5f4421182bef10f368a3e5c73258d
Closes-bug: #1465268

commit_message:
Remove predecessor column from raw_template.

This column is never used. The logic to retrieve the previous template
for rollback is based on stack table's prev_template_id.

Change-Id: Ib0af21502d0cc94613b3963d6ccdeffbc8103f6b

commit_message:
Change OSTF platfrom tests path in service tests

Related fix was merged in ostf that include
renaming from platform_tests to tests_platform
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/191737/

this patch includes updated in service tests
for ostf test execution

Change-Id: I766e1cd4558b080b22e841cb0a89b79eec02c977
Related-Bug: #1465238

Ignore my previous comment regarding 'put_string' - that's a method on a proton Data class, we'd have to monkey around a bit more with the message setup if we go that route.

I actually think this may be a bug in our driver.  That json dump is being written 'on the wire' as a variable length binary type (code 0xa0), which isn't correct, since the data is actually UTF8.  It should be sent with code 0xa1/0xb1 - UTF8 text data.

Proton sees the data as being a python2 str type, which can represent binary as well as text, and chooses the least common denominator (binary) - that's why it's being encoded as vbin.   This means, given the exact same code, a python2 client will produce vbin data, and a python3 client will sent utf8 for the same message.

I think we should fix the driver to cast/convert the json dump to unicode when we set the message.body.  If we do that, setting the 'inferred' flag shouldn't be necessary."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-15 17:54:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Verified-1

commit_message:
Use `inferred=True` by default

Rabbitmq's amqp1.0 plugin doesn't have support for vbin8, which is the
default encoding used by qpid-proton. In order to workaround this issue
we should use inferred=True.

Closes-bug: #1465409
Change-Id: Id265917244d7e152c5e13a10df367a3e59de8e50

commit_message:
Set permissions on user_secrets.yml to 0600

The permissions on the user_secrets file are too open, adjust this so that
after using pw-token-gen.py it sets the file to be 0600 for
user_secrets.yml and the backup tar file that is created. Additionally,
add a note in the README to recommend adjusting the permissions when not
utilising the pw-token-gen.py

Change-Id: I90ffacd83a89a92f48cf160e5b351e1254e9c73a
Closes-Bug: #1461997
(cherry picked from commit 3f8905caee8a0ec1afe90ba6df9b91aca14c67ec)

commit_message:
Enable amqp's protocol unit tests everywhere

Now that python-qpid-proton has taken an approach similar to zmq's, it's
possible to install it in boxes where the C libraries are not present in
the system. This patch takes advantage of that to enable amqp protocol's
tests everywhere.

Change-Id: Ibce4c791aafadf45fa876d6a4f5373fde94769ff

commit_message:
Don't raise exception from set_failed_state()

deploy_utils.set_failed_state() shouldn't raise any exceptions because
it is used to handle a failed deployment, and we want the node's
last_error to be set.

Instead, in the very rare (if ever) case that the call to
task.process_event() fails, we'll log an exception and continue.

Change-Id: I8f02577de5a5bce34608882f61b5b26f5b998fad
Closes-Bug: #1461670

commit_message:
Separate quota_classes client from quotas client

Each resource should be implemented in each separated module.
quota_classes and quotas are different resources like
  os-quota-class-sets
  os-quota-sets
So this patch separates quota_classes client from quotas client.

Partially implements blueprint consistent-service-method-names

Change-Id: Icd98294c7a161f5c8c1d7202df9f3e6d9daee1d9

I'm pretty naive about neutron and the way various things plug into it, but is it possible to get this data from talking to the neutron api directly rather than the plumgrid api?

If the plumgrid api has specific data in it that the neutron api cannot provide, can you describe those specific in the spec?"}, {'account_id': 8279, 'date': '2015-06-02 04:36:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Hi Chris,

Thanks a lot for the review. 

So I have written this spec keeping the architecture of different OpenStack projects and components in view. Where Neutron would provide Networking APIs and plugins in Neutron provide mapping of Networking APIs to plugin backend interfaces. Similarly, for Ceilometer Networking Metering Drivers, the idea is to use the Driver to provide mapping between Ceilometer API and backend interfaces. So Neutron to be used for Network Provisioning/Management and Ceilometer for Network Monitoring/Metering. 

I have deliberately not added any details of what kind of meters this driver will support because the idea is to not any meters which are outside the scope of Neutron ecosystem. I will start another effort to add different types of network meters, which make sense for Neutron specific ecosystem and are not vendor specific, so all the Neutron plugins can utilize those. For example, statistics of Router interface or packets passed/dropped of particular security group or security group rule.

If we follow the path of Ceilometer talking to Neutron and Neutron talking to backend, then we are adding redundant APIs in Neutron to support network monitoring. With the approach I have proposed, we keep it as per the design purpose of both the projects. 

In the end, we will have a clean way to separate between metering options (router-ifc-stats, sec-group-stats, port-stats etc) and drivers using them.

To summarize:
- this spec is to only define interface between Ceilometer and driver backend through client. No vendor specific meters are added.
- a separate effort to introduce types of network meters which make sense for Neutron networking.

Hope that clarifies. Please let me know if needs more discussion, I will be happy to discuss. Also, I will add all this detail in the spec as I realize this is important to make sure accurate information is captured. Again, thanks for the review; this is a very important point we should capture in the spec. 

Thanks,
Fawad Khaliq'}, {'account_id': 8279, 'date': '2015-06-02 04:52:13.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 8279, 'date': '2015-06-02 04:53:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

Updated the spec with details on the point Chris raised.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-02 04:55:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Verified+1

also, can we add some neutron cores to this spec? i don't have any knowledge  of PLUMgrid so i'd be more confident with approval from experts :)"}, {'account_id': 8279, 'date': '2015-06-10 06:11:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

Sure thing. I have added emagana in the reviewers to clarify :)

Just to give some background, PLUMgrid Neutron Plugin has been part of Neutron since Grizzly [1].

Thanks for addressing my comments. I wish I could +2 but from the Neutron side, you are all done!'}, {'account_id': 6537, 'date': '2015-06-11 07:14:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

adding Kyle,

i'm ok with having this in ceilometer but what are the chances in the future neutron can do something like nova, periodic metrics done by neutron itself (see my comment on patchset 6)

with ODL/OpenContrail and now this, i think we'll get to a point where Ceilometer's core team will be incapable of properly reviewing the neutron driver code (not that we're that ept currently)."}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2015-06-12 21:11:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

Gordon, I hear you. My advice is that you either move this back into Neutron, such that the data is provided over the ceilomter/neutron interface and expsoed via ceilometer APIs. Alternatively, you'll need to likely make this pluggable so these can run out of tree, or you're going to see an explosion of network drivers in Ceilometer. Best to get in front of this before the gate opens and the deluge starts."}, {'account_id': 8279, 'date': '2015-06-16 06:16:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

Kyle, 

Thanks a lot for the review. I agree with your concern since we had to go through a lot of work in Neutron to manage drivers in a scalable fashion.

On Ceilometer to interface with Neutron APIs: this is definitely the ultimate goal and I have mentioned this in the spec as well. However, defining and implementing this model is going to be a big effort, which we might not be able to see reach completion very soon. 

The alternative approach seems like a good option, where all network metering drivers live out of tree and we just define their loading mechanism for metering pipeline in Ceilometer (very similar to how it is in Neutron today). This way all the driver specific details will live outside the Ceilometer repo and only the config and enablement of these drivers in define in Ceilometer for now. 

Gordon, I will be happy to propose instructions on how to go about the alternative approach and have it reviewed by Ceilometer team so in future, if anyone would like to introduce a new driver, they can use the models documented. The approach Kyle suggested is quite clean in terms of what lives in tree and what live outside and it has been tried and tested in Neutron. 

Please let me know if any concerns.

Thanks,
Fawad'}, {'account_id': 8279, 'date': '2015-06-16 09:08:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Workflow-1

Reviewers,

Had a chat with Gordon over this. We will go with alternative approach suggested by Kyle. I will write a spec on how to introduce driver in a pluggable fashion that driver code lives out of tree. 

Thanks,
Fawad'}, {'account_id': 8279, 'date': '2015-06-16 09:08:23.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Fix fuel_syntax_check.sh for Mac OS X

The find command in OS X requires a path be specified or it will print
an error message. This change adds '.' to the command so that it will
properly run under Mac OS X. Additionally this change adds some error
messgaging to help identify where failures might occur.

Change-Id: Ib4dafcd5ab5b98b9602cc2f1ae44550b5b780556

(3 comments)

I think this is a great improvement over the more far reaching spec that it replaces, but reading through it raised a lot of questions in my mind about how we are doing transformation and managing polling in general. Given that we are planning to extract agents to their own repos do we have an opportunity here to make some big changes and clean things up.

I think it might make sense for pollsters to _not_ do transformation, to only configure themselves for what they will poll, poll it, and then drop a notification. The notification agents _only_ will do transformations.

Is that possible by the laws of physics?

My comments within explain some of the thinking on why this might be a good idea.'}, {'account_id': 13560, 'date': '2015-06-05 16:16:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

(3 comments)

@cdent: Inline responses to your comments.

Refactoring the polling agents to not do transformation is good from point of view of separating agents in thier repos as it minimizes dependencies on pipeline, while not completely eliminating it, as they still need the pipeline to figure out what to poll.

That said, this sounds like a considerable change to the polling agent behavior and deserves its own blueprint. Thoughts?'}, {'account_id': 6537, 'date': '2015-06-09 05:13:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

i actually still like cdent's idea about processing on the notification end... i just don't have the hardware currently to prove the additional requeue is a non-issue

While we were talking about this in the ceilo meeting I realized I have another probably very minor reservation about this change, such that it needs to be clear that the feature of dynamic reloading can be optional.

Consider a small openstack installation where I edit my pipeline.yaml by hand. Since I'm using my editor and I'm just that kind of guy I habitually save the file while I'm in it and thinking about what I'm doing. Under that circumstance I don't want a reload to happen until I say so. The easiest way for me to control that is for the dynamic reload to be disabled and for me to just do a restart of the service.

That option needs to remain (perhaps it's already specified but I wanted to note it)."}, {'account_id': 13560, 'date': '2015-06-11 15:29:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

commit_message:
Dynamic pipeline configuration using file reloading

By enhancing Ceilometer to monitor pipeline file
configuration, Ceilometer can be made to dynamically
activate/deactivate meters, collection targets or similar
functions, have distinctly different configurations for
multiple nodes in different environments and can be
updated with new collection targets “on-the-fly”.

blueprint reload-file-based-pipeline-configuration
Change-Id: I326fb42be1fe0fd61626dcc6a866569639f58f35

I like Ken'ichi's suggestion of not even passing the parameter to Neutron if the user doesn't specify it to us.  How much work would that actually take to implement?  Also, could we not pass those parameters to Neutron, or would Neutron treat that as an error as well?"}, {'account_id': 6167, 'date': '2015-06-15 01:11:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Hi Kevin,

If not passing any parameter value to Neutron, Neutron creates a security group without name and description like:

 $ curl -g -i -X POST http://192.168.11.62:9696/v2.0/security-groups.json -d '{"security_group": {}}' [..]
 [..]
 $ neutron  security-group-show c2316e97-c5e2-4751-ae0f-c145da2fc67d
 +----------------------+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
 | Field                | Value                                                              |
 +----------------------+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
 | description          |                                                                    |
 | id                   | c2316e97-c5e2-4751-ae0f-c145da2fc67d                               |
 | name                 |                                                                    |

The interesting point is the validation ways around this(security_group) are different between Nova and Neutron.
The name parameter is required on Nova API, but the name parameter is optional on Neutron API.
So if not passing any parameters to Neutron, no problem.

BTW, current Nova doesn't consider Neutron returns BadRequest response and a server internal error happens if receiving it.
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/189541 is trying to fix it. I'm happy if you take a look at it :)'}, {'account_id': 15237, 'date': '2015-06-16 08:04:17.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

Abandoning Change as Ken'ichi Ohmichi's fix is a better solution"}, {'account_id': 6167, 'date': '2015-06-16 09:00:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Thanks for giving me a chance.

The other candidate is I45c92d77c083838fbb7c5146e43c3b661e14c42d'}]

commit_message:
Changing default value of description from None to empty string

When the user is creating/updating a security group if he 
doesn't give a value for the description field nova uses 
None as the default value for the field. This cannot be 
parsed by the neutron client and it throws an neutron 
exception. So changing the value from None to empty string as 
neutron accepts a empty string in the description field

Change-Id: If5139b1a7f8aac534bd3ed13fc35994f68a4674d
Closes-Bug: #1460875

commit_message:
Python 3: use dict.values instead of dict.itervalues

This works with both Python 2 and 3, and should not have any performance
impact.

Change-Id: I2a14945c60de513b91c6f022ff5dcc503ce2a8ad
Blueprint: neutron-python3

commit_message:
devstack: do not run update-db on a compute node

When the devstack plugin is run, but q-scv is not
enabled (like on a compute node), we should not
run xxx-db-manage.

Change-Id: I6551da1020758132fd747ef119d33c3c4cb270f7

commit_message:
Split environment file into component parts

This patch splits the monolithic openstack_environment file
into component parts, making them easier to understand and
manipulate.

Change-Id: I45887599bd887a272798047f9ad650d4811ab380
Closes-Bug: #1463862

commit_message:
Merge tag '2015.1.0'

This is a null-merge of the 2015.1.0 release tag back into the master
branch so that the 2015.1.0 tag will appear in the git commit history of
the master branch. It contains no actual changes to the master branch,
regardless of how our code review system's UI represents it. Please
ask in #openstack-infra if you have any questions, and otherwise try
to merge this as quickly as possible to avoid later conflicts on the
master branch.

Change-Id: I13616ea7dd533242c12b9bf4a8af9f45c3d1afa3

commit_message:
Add get_events to OVSDB monitor

OVSDB monitor can generate the events that the OVS agent
needs to process (device added or updated). Instead of
notifying only that a change occurred and that polling
is needed, pass the events to the agent

Change-Id: I3d17bf995ad4508c4c6d089de550148da1465fa1
Partially-Implements: blueprint restructure-l2-agent

commit_message:
Wait until service thread is done on service stop

In order to be able to perform graceful shutdown of services, we need
to wait for all the current service threads to finish before exiting
from the service process.

Oslo.service provides this facility through it's wait() method, so we
need to call it in Cinder Service stop() method which gets called when
graceful shutdown is requested by sending the process SIGINT or SIGTERM.

Partial-Bug: 1464822
Change-Id: I972b80251cebe353f9d89ff4e05db8d029ef5e73

[{'created': '2015-06-10 17:27:17.000000000', 'message': "Configure DB addresses for each service

To enable partitioning of DB traffic by-service, each service needs to
use a custom connection string. Defaulting the service address to a
common galera_address makes things continue to work by default.

While the galera_address could be overridden on a container or host
basis this requires repeating that behavior across each infra node in
the inventory. Providing service-specific connection address variables
simplifies the management somewhat for large deployments and may reduce
error rates.

The service install playbooks now default the service-specific variables
instead of galera_address to the internal lb vip from inventory to
maintain the ease-of-use currently available.

Any value for a service-specific variable set in user_variables.yml will
override the value in the playbook's vars to provide selective
customization as needed.

Change-Id: I4c98bf906a0c1cb11ddd41277a855dce22ff646a

commit_message:
Configure DB addresses for each service

To enable partitioning of DB traffic by-service, each service needs to
use a custom connection string. Defaulting the service address to a
common galera_address makes things continue to work by default.

While the galera_address could be overridden on a container or host
basis this requires repeating that behavior across each infra node in
the inventory. Providing service-specific connection address variables
simplifies the management somewhat for large deployments and may reduce
error rates.

The service install playbooks now default the service-specific variables
instead of galera_address to the internal lb vip from inventory to
maintain the ease-of-use currently available.

Any value for a service-specific variable set in user_variables.yml will
override the value in the playbook's vars to provide selective
customization as needed.

Closes-Bug: 1462529

commit_message:
Updates the container build process

The container build process needs to make sure that the service
sources are correctly setup and updated prior to running any other
playbooks.

The modification here is nessisary to break out the process for the
proxy create, apt sources deployment, the update of those sources
and keys, container upgrades and the installation of python2.7 for
use with Ansible. This also allows for better debugging of a failure
in container create as we'll now be able to tell where in the process
a failure happens and be able to use tags to resolve it.

Change-Id: I36be437303a73bbc98a1cd5297f6c65591653cd7
Closes-Bug: 1464771

commit_message:
Prevent agent hangs if ohai does not return disks

Instead of freeze we got all data without disks now.
Current timeout - 30 sec.

Co-Authored-By: Mike Scherbakov (mihgen) <mscherbakov@mirantis.com>
Change-Id: I65d1b570cd01e12b521403c6d6e990043eb2c2ab
Closes-Bug: #1396086

commit_message:
Revert "Switch from MySQL-python to PyMySQL"

The failure rate with neutron is too high to keep this
as the default.

Related-Bug: #1464612

This reverts commit f08e9f1f53efa97e07f21ca72a940fcbeb4570e5.

Change-Id: If6d08e9f216ca90df882de8f27f9103fa4889c98

commit_message:
Sort instances if possible inside an host aggregate

Simple use case: Reduce the licence cost
Windows licences are billed by host or by socket. The goal is to stack all
Windows instances on the same hosts as much as possible without creating a
new host aggregate.

As much as possible means this is a best effort feature, if nova can place
this new Windows instance on a compute where other Windows are running, do
it. If not, spawn it where you want or on a empty compute to identify it
as « preferred widows compute » for future windows spawn.

This use case could be extended to many other situations, every time you
have a preferred situation with no hard restrictions.

Co-Authored-By: Michael Still <mikal@stillhq.com>

Change-Id: I261bcb802573406f0aca5a87606e4dcca877301b

commit_message:
External net should also be flat, unless segmentation_id is found

If we do not pass the network_type:flat param, the ext-net will
be created as a vlan when vlan is chosen as tenant network type,
because the single physical_network we have defined in neutron
(datacentre) is also the one used for tenant vlans.

Change-Id: Iabbcd2493a497a542514085eeb68ae653c0c77a6
Depends-On: Ieb1a9842410ecf4e89af075a4190c3a28036df9c

commit_message:
Add BondInterfaceOvsOptions parameter

This patch adds a new BondInterfaceOvsOptions to the
bond-with-vlans network config templates. This can
be used to configure things like LACP or the bonding mode
via a nested stack heat parameter.

The patch also removes the hard coded ovs_options relating
to both bond-with-vlans and single-nic-with-vlans configurations
which do not actually require this setting to be hard coded
because by default OVS trunks vlan ports automatically.

Change-Id: I3effbccba8ed7ed28d6ba715e5709275d4e7f984

commit_message:
network/config storage role fixes

None of the storage roles have Heat parameters for the bridge
name. Instead of wiring in Heat parameters for bridge name
this patch hard codes the bridge name for the storage roles
to 'br-storage'.

This functionally fixes the network config scripts for each
of the storage roles.

For the single-nic-vlans storage roles we also remove
the 'bond1' reference which was also incorrectly specified.

Change-Id: I460d1a17e44ee49e960117ec85edd3ae25894333

commit_message:
Add support for isolating swift storage nets

This patch updates the Puppet Swift storage role
so that it supports network isolation. By default
all traffic still flows on the ctlplane network
but if network isolation is enabled then network
traffic will flow over the configured storage_mgmt
network interface.

This patch also fixes a few critical issues with
the swift storage role that prevented it from
working:
 - oac_data for the swift devices was overriding the
   data provided in the swift_devices_and_proxy
   hieradata file.
 - the role was missing declarations to load hieradata
   files for swift_devices_and_proxy and all_nodes
 - The required snmpd settings were not getting set
   correctly in the 'object' hiera data file.

With all of these changes the Swift storage role
works correctly with and without network isolation.

Change-Id: I541abb2604380f603bba91ad88e54783ee450a8f

commit_message:
Remove external bridge from Compute nodes

This change modifies overcloud-resource-registry-puppet.yaml to
use net-config-noop.yaml as the default os-net-config template
for compute nodes. The current default of net-config-bridge.yaml
will set up a br-ex on the compute nodes. Since we are not using
DVR that is not needed.

Change-Id: I4e149a4f5a6d19e94e8c0245f52677f92f22d3ec

Isolate network traffic for Nova VNC proxy

This patch makes it possible to configure the isolated network
for the Nova vnc proxy client.

commit_message:
Add 'sysfsutils' package persistenlty

  The sysfsutils is required by 'osnailyfacter/modular/netconfig'
  module that generates the error pointed out by the bug: #1462216.
  This is due to the fact that no MOS packages are depend on
  'sysfsutils' and therefore it is not installed on local repos
  and the `fuel-createmirror' call without arguments removed
  upstream Ubuntu mirrors.

Change-Id: I6ddfe50e0fb81584e9228d973a67be03c97f2564
Closes-Bug: #1462216

commit_message:
Move create_ports to NodeInfo

Makes code more consistent and fixes bug with ironicclient error
reporting.

Also make NodeInfo.ports() return a dict to be more useful
for callers (like process.py).

Change-Id: I6ba587a31e839aba511c16fbf93047c7fdc54cc2
Closes-Bug: #1464184

commit_message:
Parameter can not be test in Huawei driver

In test_huawei_nas.py:
The 'Call' function of the parameters('data') can not be
test. Because of the variable('data') is assigned None in line 93.
So modify the variable name from 'data' to 'result'.

Change-Id: I8243ed3c59fbef76ebc1991286deb5c08fe813c3
Closes-Bug: #1465507

commit_message:
Provide hook into process when a node isn't found

Nodes that don't exist in the inspector node cache maybe still be
booted and return inspection information to process, this patch allows
an operator to hook into the point when the not found error is thrown
so that they may handle that information in anyway they decide to.

Change-Id: Ib17491a8201cf534d498c68d916b5b37b07f5ff6
Implements: blueprint node-not-found-hook

commit_message:
Add attribute type for heat resources

Add type field to the schema of the heat resources.
Also added Integer type to attributes schema.

Change-Id: Icd09f28a29a52be1904f76887a37c7f17786c4a6
Implements: blueprint add-type-in-attributes-schema

monotonic has only one release: the version 0.1. I'm not confident in the version number :-/ The project only has one commit!

https://github.com/atdt/monotonic/commits/master

There are other projects to get a monotonic clock:

* https://pypi.python.org/pypi/Monotime
* https://pypi.python.org/pypi/Monoclock

Monotime is still hosted on code.google.com which is closing :-/

Monoclock looks a little bit more active...

There is also https://github.com/gavinbeatty/python-monotonic-time but it doesn't look to be on PyPI :-/

I wrote and implemented the PEP 418 which adds time.monotonic() (and other functions). I backported the implementation to Python 2 but I never advertised it.

https://bitbucket.org/haypo/misc/src/tip/python/pep418.py

ctypes is slower than functions implemted in C. Maybe a C extension would help for that.

Sorry, I don't want to stop your efforts. There are only my random thoughts on the topic.

Maybe there are not enough standards and I should write my own library on PyPI! (publish pep418.py and rework it, I wrote it long time ago!)"}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2015-06-10 22:24:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

https://github.com/celery/kombu/blob/3.0/kombu/five.py#L37

Probably a bunch of others to.

I even thought maybe this should go in six once, but author didn't seem to like that...

commit_message:
Add monotonic as a requirement.

This is needed so that oslo.incubator can use a monotonic timer for
loopingcall, instead of time.time().

Change-Id: Ia802cf5bc605aa428596731d86d995e75d4fdd59
Related-Bug: #1450438

commit_message:
Added correct URL to edit QoS spec

Not able to edit the QoS spec since we are getting 'NoReverseMatch' exception.

The Exception thrown because the given URL is not correct.

This patch adding the correct URL to edit the QoS spec.

Change-Id: I0381ea343494be3449a8036b99fcbba98d893cb9
Closes-Bug: #1465185

commit_message:
Adding django-babel plugin to Horizon

Dependency allow custom extracting of Django messages using Babel.
This plugin architecture allows for future extraction for AngularJS.

Change-Id: Iaa835b03af3929b7314b174210079c34de976755
Partially-Implements: blueprint angular-translate-makemessages

commit_message:
Create a Heat-specific VIP for Pacemaker HA

This change modifies the parameters that determine which virtual IP
the Heat API uses. If there are no isolated networks, a virtual IP
on the 'ctlplane' network will be created. If the isolated network
referenced in ServiceNetMap for the Heat API exists, then a VIP
will be created on that network for Heat. For non-puppet deployments
the noop.yaml port will pass through the Controller ctlplane IP.

Change-Id: I4266aea3e0c60a12ecf24c6789c78b6f58b8300e

commit_message:
Remove VERBOSE global state.

Instead pass a verbose closure down, which while one more parameter
will prevent any skew in future unit tests.

Change-Id: I310a8fa185b2381a43b28c92ddc3f08e3c6ba035

commit_message:
Don't write partial requirements files.

If we detected nonstandard requirements we were previously rewriting
half the requirements file, making this non-idempotent: all the
subsequent contents was being lost.

Change-Id: If550d98fcab33a915bd44347bac1b538386d691f

Thanks for bringing it up! I think we should generalize booting temporary ramdisks (e.g. deploy and cleaning), so that we have 2 cases:

1. {prepare,tear_down}_maintenance_ramdisk(task, ramdisk_info) ("maintenance" part is subject to bikeshedding)

2. {prepare,tear_down}_instance_boot(task)

my expectation is that boot interface should not care about which particular ramdisk we boot.

also blocking this until spec is approved for L'}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2015-03-23 09:57:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Hi Ramesh,

Thanks for the patch, I also don't think that the boot interface should care about which ramdisk it should boot. The methods specific for each ramdisk seems overkill, maybe we could work with parameters to make a differentiation of what to boot?"}, {'account_id': 9315, 'date': '2015-03-23 10:34:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Yeah, Agree with you Dmitry and Lucas.  May be we can have

  prepare_maintanence_ramdisk(operation='<deploy or cleaning>', parameters={<parameters>}).

That seems to be enough for me."}, {'account_id': 10239, 'date': '2015-03-23 11:42:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I don't think we need 'operation'. Why can't boot interface be completely operation-agnostic? E.g. to be used in some vendor passthru (DRAC might require one for example)."}, {'account_id': 9315, 'date': '2015-03-24 05:59:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Dmitry, I still think the boot interface has to be aware of the operation - there is a difference in how it sets up the ramdisk for cleaning and deployment

 * deployment requires token file to be created whereas cleaning does not 
 * cleaning requires neutron ports to be created whereas deployment does not

I think this is something that we can infer from the current state of the machine and boot interface should be able to take this action for now - until things are sorted out such that there is no difference in the way ramdisk is booted for deployment vs ramdisk is booted for cleaning.'}, {'account_id': 10239, 'date': '2015-03-24 08:39:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

You're making assumptions based on the current code. In the future things might change, e.g.

> deployment requires token file to be created whereas cleaning does not

there's a patch to stop creating token file, and that's the way to go IMO

> cleaning requires neutron ports to be created whereas deployment does not

standalone Ironic + Neutron might require at least checking ports (or really creating them)"}, {'account_id': 9315, 'date': '2015-03-24 08:43:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Yeah, I meant we need to have these 4 methods for now:

* {prepare,tear_down}_ironic_mgmt_ramdisk_boot(task, ramdisk_opts)
* {prepare,tear_down}_instance_boot(task)

The current differences (the ones that I mentioned) we can just fit in {prepare,tear_down}_ironic_mgmt_ramdisk until the differences get sorted out. We could implement these differences by checking the nodes current state (i.e create neutron ports if node's state if CLEANING, create token file if node's state is DEPLOYING, etc)."}, {'account_id': 9315, 'date': '2015-03-26 09:26:17.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-03-26 10:00:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

commit_message:
Add boot interface in Ironic

This commit adds a new boot interface in Ironic
which can be used by deploy drivers to set up
the node to boot.

Implements: blueprint new-boot-interface
Change-Id: I0fdc0636c51a1b7803899dd09870806f1c81697e

commit_message:
Make _write_setup_py pure.

Factoring out the IO lets us look at the function more clearly, as
well as increasing testability.

Change-Id: I2366ff0ef7cba16863da9d10890a3fc60098e4d0

commit_message:
Fix multipath device discovery when UFN is enabled.

This currently returns an invalid path of `/dev/mapper/${WWID}`
when UFN is enabled leading to failures later on when we attempt to
use the device.

The output of `multipath -l ${path}` or `multipath -l ${wwid}`
should always list the correct device identifier to use with this
path as the first word on the first line.

Ignoring the test_find_multipath_device_with_error test case since
the stable/juno code base does not check for error while fetching
the associated multipath device.

Conflicts:
	cinder/brick/initiator/linuxscsi.py
	cinder/tests/brick/test_brick_linuxscsi.py

Closes-Bug: 1401799

Change-Id: Ib371b699fadcbbbb666e08eb0124c442e94a55e8
(cherry picked from commit 2fe4de571e925e26c77bffbda908f16e375b8a83)

1) In Ring-builder, Replica counts, the command
swift-ring-builder X.builder create was emphasized in the 
original.  Should it use the :guilabel: ?

Otherwise, looking good."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-15 02:21:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified-1

Hi Karen,

Re: Images - they are very similar. It is probably worth reviewing at some point, but at the moment I think it's ok so long as it matches the original version.

1) I've marked up ``swift-ring-builder X.builder create`` as a command, which matches the <command> tags in the XML version. Our theme appears not to render this as bold. I don't think :guilabel: is appropriate here as this is a CLI command.
2) The XML has <emphasis role="italic">consistency window</emphasis>, which doesn't seem to render on docs.openstack.org. Nonetheless I've used *consistency window* in the RST to match the XML source.

Are you happy with those options, or should we reconsider the markup for those situations?'}, {'account_id': 12686, 'date': '2015-06-15 02:33:54.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 10607, 'date': '2015-06-15 02:40:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-15 02:51:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

commit_message:
Replace it.next() with next(it) for py3 compat

The Python 2 next() method of iterators was renamed to __next__() on
Python 3. Use the builtin next() function instead which works on Python
2 and Python 3.
This patch was generated by the next operation of the sixer tool:
https://pypi.python.org/pypi/sixer

Change-Id: I13948f73f34c396c5cb4d55b636f12b96e62f9f9
Closes-Bug: #1464935

commit_message:
Add delete method for security group rules

Adds new API method for deleting a security group rule.

This conforms to the newly agreed upon pattern of returning True
if the resource was deleted, or False if it was not found and
could not be deleted.

Change-Id: I9c66aee078fa999a85336f600f086b93640ca96e

This function assumes that if a server has an IPv6 address, that address
is reachable from outside the cloud

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-06-13 23:56:35.000000000', 'message': 'Refactor find_nova_addresses()

Current implementation of find_nova_addresses() doesn't allow to search
just IPv4 or IPv6 addresses without specifying key_name or ext_tag too.
Moreover, when using key_name it doesn't take into account ext_tag.

commit_message:
Refactor find_nova_addresses()

Current implementation of find_nova_addresses() doesn't allow to search
just IPv4 or IPv6 addresses without specifying key_name or ext_tag too.
Moreover, when using key_name it doesn't take into account ext_tag.

This patch refactors find_nova_addresses to be more "intuitive" and to
allow searching just IPv4 or IPv6 addresses.

Change-Id: I58601a8a12ede4519869c6cf2206a934c38553f3

Move usage methods *_request to get/post/etc

HTTPClient has methods get/post/put and others, which
use json_request and raw_request, but other code uses
requests method instead of them.

commit_message:
Replace get_server_public_ip() with get_server_external_ipv4()

get_server_public_ip() just returns floating IP addresses or addresses
from a network named 'public'.

get_server_external_ipv4() tries hard to find an IPv4 address reachable
from outside the cloud.

Change-Id: I8e2c856b8f913424d3c0f20b72f240e08e4b9f62

commit_message:
Forbid deleting cluster which has policy attached to

User is not allowed to delete a cluster which still has policy
being attached to. This patch added policy check in cluster_delete
method in engine service to implement this restriction.

Change-Id: Ic4b5db68ba3e82444b10a77431ca4dc80ed6b5bd

commit_message:
Correct resource name for consolidate console API

We already have API register sub-resource 'consoles' under resource servers,
it is xen specific API:
http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/nova/tree/nova/api/openstack/compute/plugins/v3/consoles.py?id=2015.1.0#n122

This spec propose to register sub-resource 'console' under resource servers.
It really confusing we have two sub-resource, which one is 'consoles' and another
one is 'console', under resource servers.

And as the API-WG guideline
https://github.com/openstack/api-wg/blob/master/guidelines/naming.rst
The resource should be always represented as the plural. 'console' violate
that guideline.

Related to blueprint consolidate-console-api
APIImpact

Change-Id: I5fce244b4f301afcea1e2637d97982cc2bd95027

commit_message:
Hyper-V: Add storage QoS support

Hyper-V provides options to specify maximum IOPS per virtual disk
image.

By leveraging this feature, this blueprint proposes to add support
for setting QoS specs targeting instance local disks as well as
volumes exported through SMB.

bp hyperv-storage-qos

Change-Id: Icb2edcba52cb82078ee4d364422229e4e3f2fe1a

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be

    great way to learn the code base.

commit_message:
_validate_mac_address do not check if it's input is None

_validate_mac_address do not check if it's input is None, if None is
provided it will raise a TypeError which will confuse people to locate
the real problem.

Change-Id: I62444f02a6aa8baba30ae9071ee6f049d8350bd4
Closes-Bug: #1452804

commit_message:
Remove WritableLogger wrapper

With Eventlet 0.17.2, we can directly pass the logger
instance. This allows us to deprecate/remove the WritableLogger
class from oslo.log.

Change-Id: Ib7d193435584fc3631740058ed34b4df4ab23ad6
Closes-Bug: #1440773

commit_message:
libvirt: partial fix for live-migration with config drive

In current version of nova, live-migration with config drive on
local disk is forbidden due to the bug of libvirt of copying readonly
disk. However, if we use vfat as the format of config drive,
the function of live-migration works well.

In this patch, we re-open the function of live-migration to admin users.
Notice you should add 'config_drive_format=vfat' in nova.conf explicitly.

This patch doesn't solve the problem fundamentally which need further
efforts, but offers a simple and feasible workaround to user.

DocImpact

Conflicts:
        nova/virt/libvirt/driver.py

NOTE(symonds): The conflicts are due to:
        not using is_shared_instance_path or is_shared_block_storage in stable/icehouse.

Conflicts:
        nova/tests/unit/virt/libvirt/test_driver.py

NOTE(symonds): The conflicts are due to:
        libvirt_driver.LibvirtDriver().pre_live_migration() returning None on success
            instead of Spice and VNC information.
        not using is_shared_instance_path or is_shared_block_storage in stable/icehouse.

Co-Authored-By: Davanum Srinivas <davanum@gmail.com>, Matt Riedemann <mriedem@us.ibm.com>
Change-Id: I7429e12766da7f7f8d484b3a9df6247e832816b0
Partial-Bug: #1246201
(cherry picked from commit 7c4be65733e48dcf44bc306ab964fafb71b37774)

I was comparing old key to new key and was puzzled that they pretty much matched except that the new was longer and the difference was from  n-1 till the end. What is the likelihood of that?!

Moving on to the log from using this new key .. reachable from this patche' s Jenkins gate test http://logs.openstack.org/13/191313/5/check/gate-tempest-dsvm-ironic-agent_ssh-src/c7e7e50/

to find: 
that now there are no complaints about the version.
(in the past: "gpg: unknown armor header:     Version: GnuPG v2.0.20 (GNU/Linux)")

But the key is still expired. ("2015-06-13 01:44:07.479 | gpg: Note: This key has expired!")

I am guessing there must be a newer V2 key, but I did not find it with a google search. CoreOS site lists: https://coreos.com/security/image-signing-key/

Perhaps CoreOS needs to extend the life of this key or issue a new one?  Created issue: https://github.com/coreos/bugs/issues/388

Alternately is OpenStack checking for expiration incorrectly?

http://www.g-loaded.eu/2010/11/01/change-expiration-date-gpg-key/http://www.g-loaded.eu/2010/11/01/change-expiration-date-gpg-key/

Michael Marineau from CoreOS closed https://github.com/coreos/bugs/issues/388 with the following:
"The previous signing sub-key expired back in September. The key you link to includes the current signing sub key so as long as you refresh your copy you should be good to go."'}, {'account_id': 12343, 'date': '2015-06-13 06:19:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

(1 comment)

The reason why the old and new keys are the same except for an additional block is that only the signing sub-key has a limited life time and that is the part that expired. We simply added a new signing sub-key to the existing primary key.

So you don't actually need to update the key until you start using a CoreOS version signed by the newer sub-key. Until then the warning about the expired key is just expected noise. :("}, {'account_id': 10343, 'date': '2015-06-13 15:35:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

This LGTM, thank you!

I've uploaded a patch on top of this to bump the version, and the key no longer appears to be expired, as expected: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/191505/

@John, the commit message is fine. Whitespace doesn't matter. If we do want that to matter, we should have pep8 check that rather than people. Also, in the future, don't hesitate to update commit messages for small nits if that's the only reason to vote -1 on it."}, {'account_id': 10343, 'date': '2015-06-13 15:35:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review+2

commit_message:
Replace metaclass registry with explicit opt-in registry from oslo

This patch replaces Nova's magical metaclass object registry with the
one from oslo_versionedobjects.

Most of the changes here are related to test objects which previously
(and annoyingly) were automatically registered. It takes a more explicit
action to register these now, but also means we don't have to worry
about the version hash tracking picking up such objects.

There is a change to nova.exception here to copy the readonly exception
from the library, which is purely a tactic to reduce the amount of stuff
we have to change in this patch. The next patch will remove that and do
the necessary test conversions.

Related to blueprint use-oslo-objects

Change-Id: If3465f995dd05d2c01f01469b3ad9166c8362e8c

commit_message:
Allow rabbit mq kombu ssl configuration

Add the rest of the kombu ssl configuration options.

After this patch goes in, will need to update each cookbook
that uses rabbit mq to add these to the conf file.

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-06-06 16:52:44.000000000', 'message': "Add get_server_external_ipv4()

WiP: figure out how we can *know* if neutron is available.
If the provider firewalled the neutron port, but the service is in the
keystone catalog, calling neutron API will cause a timeout, eventually.
That is an unacceptable delay...

On one hand users shouldn't need to know 1k facts about the cloud they
are using, but in this case using a network-provider config in o-c-c can
really save our life. Moreover asking the user to specify what are the
*_source for their cloud (floating_ip_source secgroup_source are the
current 2 examples) is much worse than asking them just 1 thing: what
is your freaking network_provider, nova or neutron?! :)

Change-Id: I099193437d0f45cfda78923349e500e9b2e0e053

commit_message:
Add get_server_external_ipv4() to meta

It turned out we can't rely on get_server_public_ip to get an
externally reachable IP of servers because not always floating IPs
are used and not always are what the caller is looking for.

get_server_external_ipv4() tries hard to provide an IP address of the
given server that can be reached from networks that are external to
the cloud.
Unfortunately from some clouds (or for very particularly configured
servers with multiple interfaces) it could not be possible to
reliably determine those IP addresses.
Those clouds are corner cases that are not supported by
get_server_external_ipv4()

Co-Authored-By: Monty Taylor <mordred@inaugust.com>
Change-Id: I099193437d0f45cfda78923349e500e9b2e0e053

commit_message:
Add default domain to fixture.v3.V3FederationToken

Each ephemeral user is by default a member of service domain called
"Federated". We should reflect this in fixture.v3.V3FederationToken as
well.

Change-Id: I46a68048c4520e8bace4800b7635df3f8d351dd0

commit_message:
Create file /etc/default/neutron-server

Some neutron packages do not create the /etc/default/neutron-server
file, so we need to ensure that it exists to prevent errors when the
file_line resource is run.

Change-Id: I612e7fa5da7eebd8ae759e867eb8be5cebcdbe9d
Related-Bug: #1385517
Co-Authored-By: Alex Schultz <aschultz@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Refactor: move PKI-specific tests into the appropriate class

This patch moves PKI and PKIZ specific tests into a PKI specific test
class. The PKIZ test class then inherits those tests from the PKI test
class. The UUID test class no longer has to override the parent class to
skip an irrelevant test.

Change-Id: Iafb038d5ef6e380a0b48f0bc31ed0da5c526492b

commit_message:
Pass environment variables of proxy to tox

When a development environment is under a proxy, tox is failed even if
environment variables of the proxy are set.

This patch fix this problem.

See:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/189569

Change-Id: I9f88235c58422c420bbd6ba4a3d8c4a5c60db246

commit_message:
Ensure cache keys are a known/fixed length

Do not assume a token_id will result in a sane length for a memcache
key length. In cases such as Fernet, these ids can easily exceed the
limit on memcache key size. This change ensures we always use a SHA256
of the token id passed in, resulting in a fixed length cache key.

Change-Id: I550e0a1b190047438756bbf40490815a5f177ea7
Closes-Bug: #1460225

commit_message:
JSCS Cleanup - tech-debt and auth

JSCS cleanup for files in:
- horizon/static/auth
- horizon/static/framework/util/tech-debt/
- openstack_dashboard/static/dashboard/tech-debt/

NOTE: These files were previously in horizon/static/dashboard-app,
but were moved between patches, causing the seemingly random selection
of cleanups

Change-Id: I63c3c641bf42152d8ff99702078d06df22812555
Partially-Implements: blueprint jscs-cleanup

DO NOT MERGE: Add K2K federation auth plugin

federation.

commit_message:
Nova admin role

Current “admin” role in Nova and other services are pretty static.  A
user with “admin” role has the super admin privilege not only in
Nova, but other services as well.  In most organizations, compute
administrators and administrators from other services are from
distinct group of administrator.  If an organization does not allow
Nova administrators to make changes to say Cinder or Neutron, then
Nova administrators should only have a “Nova specific admin role”,
and not the super ”admin” role.

Enhance Nova policy to include Nova admin role, so that
administrators with Nova admin role can perform Nova administrative
tasks without having to take on the super "admin" role.

SecurityImpact

Change-Id: Ie8d653eed2fea244be6fa535ed6fd003ea15c2bb

commit_message:
Move registration of GenericResource to HeatTest

This patch moves registration of GenericResource to the main test class.
There are several places, where original registration was saved:
- heat/tests/autoscaling/test_lbutils.py - need to be consist with type
names of other resources which are used in test.
- heat/tests/test_environment.py - need special type name for testing
  environment mapping.
- heat/tests/test_engine_service.py - need two different types fro mapping.

Change-Id: I33bdaf3d59e573526e5ffa24086ad55be6bbe6ae

Move registration of resources to HeatTestCase

- SignalResource
